{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 04:29:37.424573", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall L3 health is good: end-to-end reachability across user subnets and the server farm is present, OSPF adjacencies are up, DHCP provided addresses and default routes, DNS is reachable and answers queries, and HTTP services (including the load balancer) are reachable.\n- Major anomaly: backend web servers are directly accessible from user hosts (both resolvable and reachable via HTTP), which contradicts the stated design that backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts.\n- Secondary observation: ICMP RTT from some server-farm sources (load balancer, web_server_2, web_server_3) to hosts shows elevated and variable latency. This does not appear to impact HTTP performance in our tests but is atypical for an internal network.\n\nFindings and evidence\n1) Host IP/DHCP/gateway configuration\n- host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.18/24, default via 10.1.1.1 (dynamic via DHCP).\n- host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.11/24, default via 10.2.1.1 (dynamic via DHCP).\n- DHCP appears functional, leases active, and correct default gateways installed.\n\n2) Reachability\n- Broad ping matrix shows 0% loss across tested pairs. Cross-area/reachability among subnets is present.\n- Notable RTT variability for some flows (see “Performance anomaly” below).\n\n3) DNS service and name resolution\n- DNS server (10.200.0.2) is listening on TCP/53 and 127.0.0.1 control port; service is up.\n- From hosts, getent resolves:\n  - web99.local -> 10.200.0.7 (load balancer)\n  - web0.local -> 10.200.0.3\n  - web1.local -> 10.200.0.4\n  - web2.local -> 10.200.0.5\n  - web3.local -> 10.200.0.6\n- This reveals backend server IPs to clients (contrary to design).\n\n4) HTTP access tests from hosts\n- host_1_1_1_1:\n  - http://web99.local: total 1.00–1.02 s (name lookup ~3–10 ms, TTFB ~200–232 ms).\n  - http://web0.local: total ~0.96–1.05 s (TTFB ~210–247 ms).\n- host_2_1_1_1:\n  - http://web99.local: total ~1.01–1.12 s (TTFB ~212–322 ms).\n  - http://web1.local: total ~1.02–1.08 s (TTFB ~217–279 ms).\n- Result: Clients can access backend web servers directly via HTTP, and performance is similar to the load balancer path.\n\n5) OSPF state (FRR routers)\n- All queried routers show Full adjacencies on expected links:\n  - Core routers have Full/DR or Full/Backup neighbor states on inter-core links.\n  - Distribution routers have Full with their upstream core.\n  - server_access_router has Full with core_3.\n- No adjacency flaps or down neighbors observed; OSPF control plane appears healthy.\n\n6) Performance anomaly (ICMP RTT variability)\n- Some sources in the server farm show elevated and highly variable ping RTTs to hosts (e.g., load_balancer avg ~18–20 ms with ranges up to ~39 ms; web_server_2 avg ~28–45 ms and web_server_3 avg ~37–79 ms to tested hosts).\n- Many host-to-host RTTs are in the 1–5 ms range, indicating the variance is not ubiquitous.\n- Despite this, HTTP timings from hosts are stable (~1.0–1.1 s total) and not showing loss.\n\nAssessment and anomaly detection\n- Functional health: Routing (OSPF), reachability, DHCP, DNS transport, and HTTP application access are functioning.\n- Policy/security anomaly: Backend web servers are directly resolvable and reachable from user hosts, which conflicts with the stated design that backend web servers should not be directly accessible. This is confirmed by:\n  - DNS responses providing A records for web0.local–web3.local to user hosts.\n  - Successful HTTP requests from hosts to backend server names.\n- Performance anomaly: Elevated ICMP RTT from certain server-farm sources to hosts suggests possible asymmetric handling, ICMP de-prioritization, queueing, or resource contention on the server path. HTTP tests did not show material impact, but the pattern is atypical.\n\nFault localization\n- Components implicated in policy anomaly:\n  - DNS server (10.200.0.2): Publishing backend host A records to clients in user subnets.\n  - server_access_router and/or distribution layer: No apparent L3 filtering between user subnets and 10.200.0.0/24 to restrict direct access to backend servers. Given OSPF advertises server subnets and connectivity is open, access control is likely missing or misapplied at server_access_router (the L3 boundary for the server farm) and/or at distribution layer ACLs.\n- Components implicated in ICMP RTT variability:\n  - Likely localized to server-side path (load_balancer, web_server_2, web_server_3) or server_access_router. Host-to-host RTT remains low. The variability appears when probing from server-farm nodes, not broadly across the network.\n\nProbable root causes\n- Primary: Policy misconfiguration allowing direct client-to-backend access. This likely comprises:\n  - DNS zone/view misconfiguration that exposes backend A records to user hosts.\n  - Missing/insufficient L3 ACLs or firewall policy at server_access_router (and/or distribution layer) to enforce that only the load balancer VIP (10.200.0.7) is reachable by user subnets, while backend servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6) are not.\n- Secondary: ICMP RTT spikes from server-farm sources likely due to traffic handling or resource contention (e.g., ICMP deprioritization, queueing on the server path or server_access_router). The behavior does not presently manifest as HTTP performance degradation but is noteworthy as a potential early signal of congestion or prioritization differences.\n\nConclusion\n- The network is operational with full routing and service reachability. However, there is a significant policy deviation: backend web servers are directly accessible from user hosts, which violates the stated design intent. This is attributable to DNS exposure of backend records and the absence of network-layer restrictions between user subnets and the server-farm backends. Additionally, sporadic high ICMP RTTs from certain server-farm nodes to hosts are observed, though with no immediate impact to HTTP service in our tests.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 43838, "output_tokens": 4851, "total_tokens": 48689, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3392}}}
